or different things like
that to create the cover

00:40:13.450 --> 00:40:16.475
and create the permission
for people to innovate.

00:40:19.325 --> 00:40:21.710
I'll take this.

00:40:21.710 --> 00:40:24.760
AUDIENCE: So I was curious, in
the research that you've done

00:40:24.760 --> 00:40:26.440
and implementation,
have you found

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:29.980
that you need to have a
radical approach to cutting out

00:40:29.980 --> 00:40:34.480
the current system and trying
to replace it with the goals

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:35.410
that you'd listed?

00:40:35.410 --> 00:40:38.890
Or do you think there's a way
to do it incrementally that just

00:40:38.890 --> 00:40:41.470
builds upon the current
system but moves it slowly

00:40:41.470 --> 00:40:43.305
towards the goals
that you've listed?

00:40:43.305 --> 00:40:44.930
JEFF WETZLER: So when
we first started,

00:40:44.930 --> 00:40:46.920
we had kind of a purist
ideological approach.

00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:49.040
It was like, you had to take
out a blank sheet of paper,

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:50.498
you had to leave
it all behind, you

00:40:50.498 --> 00:40:52.300
had to design fresh, et cetera.

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:54.430
And we do still
believe that you really

00:40:54.430 --> 00:40:56.470
do need to think about
the total environment.

00:40:56.470 --> 00:40:57.990
It's like if you were
taking a horse and buggy

00:40:57.990 --> 00:40:59.960
and you were trying to say, how
do we put an engine on that?

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:00.890
It's just not going to work.

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:02.380
You need to think holistically.

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:04.330
But over time, as we've
worked with schools

00:41:04.330 --> 00:41:06.455
and seen these different
kind of models, what we've

00:41:06.455 --> 00:41:08.290
come to appreciate is
that there's really

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:10.120
a lot of power and
components of school.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:12.820
So I don't just mean what we'd
call a point solution, just

00:41:12.820 --> 00:41:13.967
like one curriculum.

00:41:13.967 --> 00:41:15.550
But if you can take
a significant part

00:41:15.550 --> 00:41:17.740
of a kid's experience or
an adult's experience,

00:41:17.740 --> 00:41:18.857
start with that.

00:41:18.857 --> 00:41:19.940
That can make real change.

00:41:19.940 --> 00:41:21.460
And that can then open
the door to what's

00:41:21.460 --> 00:41:23.668
the next thing and the next
thing and the next thing.

00:41:23.668 --> 00:41:25.190
And pretty soon,
over several years,

00:41:25.190 --> 00:41:26.440
you can stack together things.

00:41:26.440 --> 00:41:27.590
And you step back
and you say, wow,

00:41:27.590 --> 00:41:29.298
that's a radically
different environment.

00:41:29.298 --> 00:41:31.640
But it didn't require gutting
it all from the start.

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:32.723
I appreciate the question.

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:36.993
AUDIENCE: Kind of
following up on that,

00:41:36.993 --> 00:41:38.910
how do you think about
the broader picture of,

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:41.700
I like this idea of innovating
and changing and making it more

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:46.800
individual for kids, but what
do you think about the system--

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:49.920
schools are meant to gear
towards test-- standardized

00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:51.830
testing and getting
into college.

00:41:51.830 --> 00:41:54.065
How do you think this type--

00:41:54.065 --> 00:41:55.440
how do you explain
that, I guess,

00:41:55.440 --> 00:41:59.880
as you convince schools
to incorporate this in,

00:41:59.880 --> 00:42:01.950
knowing that eventually
these kids need to work

00:42:01.950 --> 00:42:03.378
towards these types of tests?

00:42:03.378 --> 00:42:04.170
JEFF WETZLER: Yeah.

00:42:04.170 --> 00:42:06.400
So we can't ignore that.

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:08.427
The stakes for kids
are real in terms

00:42:08.427 --> 00:42:11.010
of what you get on the SAT, and
can you get access to college,

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:13.218
and can you get access to
jobs, and things like that.

00:42:13.218 --> 00:42:15.300
So nothing that
we're trying to do

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:17.850
is trying to say we should
ignore that, we should pretend

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:19.998
those things don't
exist, particularly

00:42:19.998 --> 00:42:22.040
when the playing field is
not level for all kids.

00:42:22.040 --> 00:42:24.510
Really, kids having
opportunities deeply, deeply

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:25.260
matters.

00:42:25.260 --> 00:42:26.760
So part of the way
we think about it

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:28.718
is that even if we were
just trying to optimize

00:42:28.718 --> 00:42:31.500
within the current system,
lots of these kinds of designs

00:42:31.500 --> 00:42:34.060
can increase motivation, can
be more efficient for learning,

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:35.560
et cetera, and just
kind of optimize

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:36.930
within that current system.

00:42:36.930 --> 00:42:39.670
And then at the same time,
there's a number of efforts

00:42:39.670 --> 00:42:42.437
underway to think about
measures of things

00:42:42.437 --> 00:42:44.520
that go beyond the traditional
standardized tests,

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.590
whether those are
social-emotional development,

00:42:46.590 --> 00:42:49.350
critical thinking, other
kinds of future-of-work types

00:42:49.350 --> 00:42:50.420
of competencies.

00:42:50.420 --> 00:42:52.170
And so that work really
needs to continue.

00:42:52.170 --> 00:42:54.870
And as that work
gets more legitimized

00:42:54.870 --> 00:42:57.240
and gets more momentum, I
think it will open up lots

00:42:57.240 --> 00:42:58.440
more pathways for kids, too.

00:42:58.440 --> 00:43:00.090
AUDIENCE: So I know you--

00:43:00.090 --> 00:43:02.790
kind of jumping off
of her question,

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:06.210
you're focusing a lot on
the education system, which

00:43:06.210 --> 00:43:07.500
is really nice, obviously.

00:43:07.500 --> 00:43:09.360
But I feel like
there's problems that

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:11.040
exist kind of at
the workforce level,

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:14.010
where people are judged
off of pieces of paper

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:17.490
with certain scores or
what school you went to

00:43:17.490 --> 00:43:18.970
and stuff like that.

00:43:18.970 --> 00:43:22.740
Is there a way to kind of hit
this problem from both ends?

00:43:22.740 --> 00:43:25.290
Instead of just saying, let's
get these educators better

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:27.540
and make sure the students
are better so that they can

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:29.610
get a job, but
instead, also say,

00:43:29.610 --> 00:43:33.240
hey, let's try to hire people
in a way that's not necessarily

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:34.560
just standardized, either?

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:36.060
JEFF WETZLER: It
absolutely matters.

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:38.340
And I think Google is
among the leaders in kind

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:40.170
of pushing on that
question and saying,

00:43:40.170 --> 00:43:42.087
let's not just look at
traditional transcripts

00:43:42.087 --> 00:43:44.170
or where'd you go to school
or that kind of thing,

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:45.180
but what are the skills?

00:43:45.180 --> 00:43:47.920
But the more that people
follow that lead and do that,

00:43:47.920 --> 00:43:50.130
I think the more that
opens up the possibility

00:43:50.130 --> 00:43:52.890
for the K12 system
of schools to feel

00:43:52.890 --> 00:43:56.460
even more confident in
expanding its range of outcomes

00:43:56.460 --> 00:43:58.048
that it's going for, as well.

00:43:58.048 --> 00:43:59.340
I'll leave you with this quote.

00:43:59.340 --> 00:44:00.930
"If you always do
what you always did,

00:44:00.930 --> 00:44:02.100
you'll always get
what you always got."

00:44:02.100 --> 00:44:04.058
I think we've talked a
lot about why that's not

00:44:04.058 --> 00:44:06.930
good enough for kids and for
society and for workplaces,

00:44:06.930 --> 00:44:07.523
as well.

00:44:07.523 --> 00:44:08.940
And if there's one
message I would

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:11.700
want to have you take
away, it's possible to do

00:44:11.700 --> 00:44:12.900
something different.

00:44:12.900 --> 00:44:14.550
If we design the
system one way, we

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:16.080
can design the
system another way.

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:18.030
It takes R&amp;D. It takes capacity.

00:44:18.030 --> 00:44:20.730
It takes all the things that you
all do in the work that you do.

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:21.570
But it's really possible.

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:23.028
And that's what
we're trying to do.

00:44:23.028 --> 00:44:25.785
We would love help in all kinds
of different kinds of ways

00:44:25.785 --> 00:44:26.910
and people to get involved.

00:44:26.910 --> 00:44:28.660
So there's a website
up here and whatever.

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:30.813
If you want to get
involved, please join us.

00:44:30.813 --> 00:44:32.730
It's going to take all
of us to get this done.

00:44:32.730 --> 00:44:33.540
Thank you.

00:44:33.540 --> 00:44:36.890
[APPLAUSE]

